Steinberg from Australia that's about to submit, I believe.

67
00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:05.030
That's focusing on interventional studies.

68
00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:09.049
We published a non-systematic review in August last year

69
00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:12.760
discussing the promises and pitfalls of the current MCED test,

70
00:04:13.340 --> 00:04:17.041
highlighting the challenges in translating a test that may be good at

71
00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:20.860
detecting cancer in asymptomatic individuals into an

72
00:04:20.899 --> 00:04:24.720
effective screening program that reduces cancer morbidity and/or

73
00:04:24.740 --> 00:04:26.840
mortality in the population.

74
00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:33.920
The first of those papers provided performance statistics on five

75
00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:37.800
commercial tests, all reported specificities of at least

76
00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:39.660
96.4%.

77
00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:41.130
But note,

78
00:04:42.460 --> 00:04:45.200
with a specificity of 96.4%,

79
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.930
nine times as many people will have a false positive test compared

80
00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:52.640
to a specificity of 99.6%.

81
00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:56.480
So whereas they're all very good, some are better than others.

82
00:04:57.160 --> 00:05:00.800
With one exception, the sensitivities range between 20% and 70%,

83
00:05:01.560 --> 00:05:05.400
but as I pointed out in a recent editorial, traditional test performance

84
00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:08.920
metrics are not useful for multi-cancer screening tests,

85
00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:12.950
and the estimated sensitivity will depend heavily on the mix of cancers

86
00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:13.560
included.

87
00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:18.010
Where reported, sensitivity was lower for detecting earlier

88
00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:21.890
stage than later stage cancers. One company claims

89
00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:25.200
90% sensitivity, but there's precious little

90
00:05:25.240 --> 00:05:27.659
peer-reviewed data about its test.

91
00:05:28.780 --> 00:05:32.500
So of the five tests, one is based on methylation of cell-free DNA,

92
00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:36.920
another a combination of proteins and gene mutations in

93
00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:39.560
cell-free DNA, and now they're looking at

94
00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:43.340
methylation. A third sequences

95
00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:46.860
cell-free DNA and then combines methylation, fragment length,

96
00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:50.070
fragment end motifs, and copy number variation.

97
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.540
One uses multiplex fluorescence immunocytochemistry

98
00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:58.620
to evaluate tissue-specific markers on circulating tumor cells,

99
00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:02.360
and the fifth uses electrical properties of the blood

100
00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:05.888
sample.One issue

101
00:06:05.968 --> 00:06:09.728
peculiar to multi-cancer tests is the identification of the

102
00:06:09.768 --> 00:06:13.708
tissue of origin. Some tests rely on whole body scanning in

103
00:06:13.748 --> 00:06:15.548
patients with a positive screening test.

104
00:06:16.148 --> 00:06:20.028
Others provide a supplementary result that indicates where the cancer

105
00:06:20.048 --> 00:06:23.508
may be found and directs diagnostic workup.

106
00:06:24.288 --> 00:06:27.948
For many tests, the performance of the tissue of origin identification

107
00:06:28.348 --> 00:06:30.948
in those with a true positive is excellent.

108
00:06:33.768 --> 00:06:37.428
In February, Grail announced that the NHS Galleri,

109
00:06:37.788 --> 00:06:41.648
the only randomized controlled trial of a multi-cancer screening test with a

110
00:06:41.688 --> 00:06:45.248
clinical endpoint, failed to achieve its primary endpoint, a

111
00:06:45.288 --> 00:06:49.148
statistically significant reduction in stage three and four cancers three

112
00:06:49.248 --> 00:06:51.398
years after the last participant was enrolled.

113
00:06:52.508 --> 00:06:56.028
While the result is disappointing for the field, the announcement also

114
00:06:56.088 --> 00:06:59.808
reported a favorable trend in reducing stage

115
00:06:59.888 --> 00:07:03.278
four diagnoses in high mortality cancers.

116
00:07:03.748 --> 00:07:07.548
There's also a suggestion that a reduction in

117
00:07:07.628 --> 00:07:11.548
stage four cancers increased with longer follow-up, as would be

118
00:07:11.588 --> 00:07:13.848
expected from natural history modeling.

119
00:07:15.188 --> 00:07:19.118
They also reported increased detection of stage one and two cancers and

120
00:07:19.168 --> 00:07:22.808
a substantial reduction in cancers

121
00:07:22.908 --> 00:07:24.948
presenting through emergency presentation.

122
00:07:26.348 --> 00:07:30.128
Although not the primary focus of the trial, these results point to

123
00:07:30.168 --> 00:07:32.808
clinical benefits of annual screening.

124
00:07:32.828 --> 00:07:36.088
Full results will be presented at ASCO at the end of May.

125
00:07:38.308 --> 00:07:41.718
In October last year, results from the first 25,000

126
00:07:41.788 --> 00:07:44.608
participants in PATHFINDER 2 were presented.

127
00:07:45.138 --> 00:07:48.798
The positive predicted value of a positive Galleri test was 62%,

128
00:07:49.588 --> 00:07:53.488
substantially higher than with any existing screening program or

129
00:07:53.528 --> 00:07:57.368
indeed most symptoms. Only 67%

130
00:07:57.428 --> 00:08:01.188
of people referred with urgent suspected cancer in England

131
00:08:02.088 --> 00:08:03.428
are diagnosed with cancer.

132
00:08:04.808 --> 00:08:08.728
And with 12 months follow-up, the episode sensitivity of

133
00:08:08.788 --> 00:08:12.568
the 12 types of cancer that are the focus of the test and which cause

134
00:08:12.628 --> 00:08:16.608
two-thirds of cancer deaths in the US was 74%.

135
00:08:19.488 --> 00:08:23.428
Tests based on cell-free DNA may never be able to detect

136
00:08:23.668 --> 00:08:27.098
most stage one cancers and certainly not intraepithelial

137
00:08:27.128 --> 00:08:28.548
neoplasia and adenomas.

138
00:08:29.348 --> 00:08:33.328
My lack of optimism is because such tumors don't seem

139
00:08:33.348 --> 00:08:34.208
to shed DNA.

140
00:08:35.249 --> 00:08:38.928
Modeling suggests that the limit of detection of Galleri is at roughly

141
00:08:39.268 --> 00:08:43.259
0.1% tumor fraction. Below this threshold,

142
00:08:43.889 --> 00:08:47.868
the test has very little sensitivity, whereas above it, the sensitivity

143
00:08:47.908 --> 00:08:48.788
is extremely high.

144
00:08:49.748 --> 00:08:53.068
In other words, improving the algorithms using

145
00:08:53.128 --> 00:08:56.108
AI is unlikely to make much of a difference.

146
00:08:58.308 --> 00:09:02.228
This also has positive implications in terms of overdiagnosis of

147
00:09:02.288 --> 00:09:06.248
solid tumors. Because the level of DNA shedding is a

148
00:09:06.288 --> 00:09:09.548
proxy of tumor aggressiveness, the chance of significant

149
00:09:09.628 --> 00:09:13.488
overdiagnosis from the use of such tests, multi-cancer tests,

150
00:09:13.788 --> 00:09:14.588
is very small.

151
00:09:17.728 --> 00:09:21.648
Protein markers have a role in improving sensitivity

152
00:09:21.808 --> 00:09:23.688
to early cancers.

153
00:09:24.508 --> 00:09:28.048
Whereas cell-free DNA comes from dying tumor cells, proteins

154
00:09:28.408 --> 00:09:30.648
may be produced in response to a tumor.

155
00:09:31.948 --> 00:09:35.128
For this reason, protein-based biomarkers may permit

156
00:09:35.488 --> 00:09:39.268
detection of very early cancers, albeit at the expense of reduced

157
00:09:39.288 --> 00:09:40.088
specificity.

158
00:09:41.828 --> 00:09:45.788
Similarly, even small tumors produce a substantial amount of cell-free

159
00:09:45.848 --> 00:09:49.508
microRNA secreted via exosomes and microvesicles.

160
00:09:50.588 --> 00:09:54.228
Since much microRNA is protein bound, it is more

161
00:09:54.308 --> 00:09:57.997
stable in the blood, and with a longer half-life means that it is

162
00:09:58.068 --> 00:09:59.748
more easy to detect.

163
00:10:00.698 --> 00:10:04.228
Thus, microRNA based tests are likely to be more

164
00:10:04.268 --> 00:10:07.848
sensitive to early stage tumors, but because they can be

165
00:10:07.888 --> 00:10:11.408
influenced by inflammation, they will also lack specificity.

166
00:10:16.408 --> 00:10:20.308
Several MCED tests are available commercially, but none has yet received

167
00:10:20.408 --> 00:10:21.307
FDA approval.

168
00:10:22.828 --> 00:10:26.697
The FDA granted breakthrough device designation to Guardant Health's

169
00:10:26.708 --> 00:10:30.248
Shield multi-cancer detection test in June 2025.

170
00:10:30.908 --> 00:10:34.508
Grail submitted a pre-market approval application for Galleri

171
00:10:34.588 --> 00:10:35.358
earlier this year.

172
00:10:36.428 --> 00:10:38.048
The NCI's Vanguard study

173
00:10:39.028 --> 00:10:42.568
was launched in July last year. It aims to recruit

174
00:10:42.768 --> 00:10:46.648
24,000 participants aged 45 to 75 over

175
00:10:46.688 --> 00:10:47.248
two years.

176
00:10:48.548 --> 00:10:51.678
It's a feasibility pilot designed to test the logistics,

177
00:10:51.688 --> 00:10:55.248
processes, recruitment strategies, and diagnostic workup

178
00:10:55.288 --> 00:10:55.808
pathways.

179
00:10:56.648 --> 00:10:59.968
It will test 8,000 people twice a year apart with Shield,

180
00:11:00.588 --> 00:11:03.988
8,000 with Avante, and 8,000 participants will be

181
00:11:04.028 --> 00:11:04.588
controls.

182
00:11:05.618 --> 00:11:08.108
The study is due to complete in 2029.

183
00:11:08.868 --> 00:11:12.648
The intention is to use the results to design a study of

184
00:11:13.148 --> 00:11:16.988
225,000 people, randomized controlled

185
00:11:17.048 --> 00:11:19.098
with a cancer mortality outcome.

186
00:11:19.948 --> 00:11:23.108
That trial will not complete before 2038.

187
00:11:24.148 --> 00:11:26.648
By that time, technologies will have moved on.

188
00:11:28.048 --> 00:11:31.868
By contrast, industry has been generating data at pace.

189
00:11:33.128 --> 00:11:37.068
At ASCO, Grail will present three-year follow-up on data

190
00:11:37.128 --> 00:11:40.888
of the 140,000 participant randomized controlled trial of

191
00:11:41.028 --> 00:11:43.328
MCED screening versus usual care.

192
00:11:44.168 --> 00:11:46.268
And in answer to a question on Monday,

193
00:11:47.988 --> 00:11:51.758
Tom, Exact Sciences said that they are planning to do a randomized

194
00:11:51.808 --> 00:11:53.447
controlled trial. I don't know when.

195
00:11:57.448 --> 00:12:01.338
PATHFINDER reported on the psychosocial impact of multi-cancer screening.

196
00:12:02.148 --> 00:12:06.068
Anxiety scores were increased at the time of disclosure of positive

197
00:12:06.128 --> 00:12:06.648
results,

198
00:12:07.788 --> 00:12:10.368
but returned to baseline within 12 months.

199
00:12:11.128 --> 00:12:13.808
No changes were observed in those with a negative test

200
00:12:13.818 --> 00:12:19.078
result.The

201
00:12:19.118 --> 00:12:22.948
clinical need is for a screening test that can find potentially fatal cancers

202
00:12:23.338 --> 00:12:25.458
while still treatable with a curative intent.

203
00:12:26.358 --> 00:12:30.078
The harms of periodic screening should be small compared to the benefits.

204
00:12:30.558 --> 00:12:34.498
Ideally, the test should work for rare cancers too, because it

205
00:12:34.538 --> 00:12:38.178
is only through multi-cancer tests that we can ever consider

206
00:12:38.218 --> 00:12:42.018
screening for rare cancers, which combined account for about a

207
00:12:42.098 --> 00:12:43.978
quarter of all cancer deaths in the US.

208
00:12:45.278 --> 00:12:48.858
We must consider not only the frequency of harms, but also their

209
00:12:48.898 --> 00:12:49.518
magnitude.

210
00:12:50.478 --> 00:12:54.378
If a false positive test results in a CT scan or a

211
00:12:54.418 --> 00:12:56.678
colonoscopy, it does little harm.

212
00:12:57.538 --> 00:13:01.318
If it requires surgical removal of a nodule, that is much more

213
00:13:01.378 --> 00:13:02.058
concerning.

214
00:13:03.438 --> 00:13:07.238
Further, to prevent a diagnostic odyssey or exposure to relatively

215
00:13:07.298 --> 00:13:10.978
high levels of radiation, a positive screening test should be

216
00:13:11.018 --> 00:13:14.277
accompanied by a result that helps to locate the cancer.

217
00:13:16.278 --> 00:13:19.978
If we think of screening as a series of sieves, tests based on

218
00:13:19.998 --> 00:13:22.998
cell-free DNA may be regarded as a very coarse sieve.

219
00:13:23.698 --> 00:13:27.378
They only pick up big cancers, but almost everything they do

220
00:13:27.458 --> 00:13:29.117
find is likely to be cancer.

221
00:13:30.098 --> 00:13:33.958
We also need a very fine sieve, a biomarker like

222
00:13:34.018 --> 00:13:37.858
amino acids or microRNAs, that can identify people with

223
00:13:38.438 --> 00:13:42.268
early and even pre-cancer, but which may also select a

224
00:13:42.318 --> 00:13:44.038
lot of people who don't have cancer.

225
00:13:46.518 --> 00:13:50.418
Consider a screening test with 90% sensitivity to cancers

226
00:13:50.458 --> 00:13:53.548
that might become symptomatic over the next three years and

227
00:13:53.778 --> 00:13:57.518
70% for those that might become symptomatic between three and

228
00:13:57.898 --> 00:13:58.818
10 years later.

229
00:14:00.158 --> 00:14:03.998
Even if the specificity was only 80%, a

230
00:14:04.018 --> 00:14:07.278
biennial screening with such a test might be extremely useful.

231
00:14:07.958 --> 00:14:11.738
We might screen every six months with a very specific test,

232
00:14:11.858 --> 00:14:15.738
those who identified at high risk, and annually those at moderate

233
00:14:15.818 --> 00:14:16.018
risk.

234
00:14:17.558 --> 00:14:21.118
If the sensitivity but not specific test also

235
00:14:21.158 --> 00:14:24.758
identified site of origin, one might triage with a

236
00:14:24.798 --> 00:14:28.778
single-site screening test such as colonoscopy or low-dose

237
00:14:28.818 --> 00:14:29.458
chest CT.

238
00:14:33.438 --> 00:14:37.238
In preparing this talk, I asked Google AI what Ruth would say

239
00:14:37.598 --> 00:14:38.518
about the future

240
