00:15:19.438 --> 00:15:23.158
public benefit rather than minimizing patient harm, since, in my

254
00:15:23.198 --> 00:15:27.108
opinion, used carefully, these technologies have been shown to have

255
00:15:27.458 --> 00:15:31.418
minimal harms. Indeed, it is the potential harms that are being

256
00:15:31.538 --> 00:15:33.058
hyped in the scientific journals.

257
00:15:35.198 --> 00:15:39.138
We need to go faster because there are 2.6

258
00:15:39.178 --> 00:15:43.078
million cancer deaths in Europe and North America each

259
00:15:43.158 --> 00:15:43.418
year.

260
00:15:44.538 --> 00:15:48.318
The results of the main Vanguard study will not be available for at least

261
00:15:48.358 --> 00:15:50.618
12 years after NHS Galleri.

262
00:15:51.738 --> 00:15:55.678
Suppose MCED screening could cut cancer mortality in a population

263
00:15:55.698 --> 00:15:56.638
by 8%.

264
00:15:57.758 --> 00:16:01.658
Had the results been strongly positive, the go slow approach

265
00:16:01.698 --> 00:16:04.858
would have cost 2.5 million premature deaths.

266
00:16:06.038 --> 00:16:09.878
If the trial results are negative, having conducted it

267
00:16:09.978 --> 00:16:11.778
faster does not change the harms.

268
00:16:13.158 --> 00:16:16.818
If the trial is falsely positive and we start evaluating

269
00:16:16.878 --> 00:16:20.658
screening at scale, what is the worst that might happen before we

270
00:16:20.738 --> 00:16:21.718
realize our mistake?

271
00:16:22.638 --> 00:16:25.218
We could waste a few billion dollars on screening,

272
00:16:26.038 --> 00:16:28.858
but losses of that magnitude are common on the stock market.

273
00:16:30.698 --> 00:16:34.578
Maybe 100,000 people would have had a positive test before we

274
00:16:34.618 --> 00:16:35.558
realize our error.

275
00:16:37.118 --> 00:16:40.118
They would have had transient anxiety because of that test result.

276
00:16:40.798 --> 00:16:44.578
Most will have had imaging or endoscopy to rule out cancer,

277
00:16:44.918 --> 00:16:47.158
but very few will have been seriously harmed.

278
00:16:48.798 --> 00:16:51.778
Many will have had cancer diagnosed earlier than it would have been, but

279
00:16:51.858 --> 00:16:53.658
overdiagnosis is unlikely.

280
00:16:54.478 --> 00:16:58.178
Based on what we know about these tests, about the harms of Galleri,

281
00:16:59.038 --> 00:17:02.178
we can quantify that the harms are not great.

282
00:17:03.398 --> 00:17:07.278
Suppose screening works, but its rollout is delayed by 12 years.

283
00:17:07.959 --> 00:17:10.959
What will happen on the impact on society?

284
00:17:11.838 --> 00:17:13.838
Those with the best healthcare will get

285
00:17:15.318 --> 00:17:17.959
screening of the new test privately.

286
00:17:18.547 --> 00:17:22.418
But those who are health deprived, those who are most likely to be

287
00:17:22.598 --> 00:17:26.398
diagnosed with a late-stage cancer, will not benefit.

288
00:17:26.418 --> 00:17:29.838
Health inequalities will widen, and society will become more

289
00:17:29.858 --> 00:17:30.638
divided.

290
00:17:37.598 --> 00:17:41.218
I would screen a million people a year in the US as part of a

291
00:17:41.258 --> 00:17:43.558
pragmatic trial to generate more evidence.

292
00:17:44.278 --> 00:17:48.238
I would focus on people aged 60 to 74 with the greatest risk

293
00:17:48.278 --> 00:17:50.358
of being diagnosed with a stage four cancer.

294
00:17:51.418 --> 00:17:55.328
I would offer screening to those attending for targeted lung screening,

295
00:17:56.278 --> 00:17:59.878
attending a stop smoking clinic, a weight management clinic, or a type 2

296
00:17:59.898 --> 00:18:03.358
diabetes clinic. I would invite people living in the most

297
00:18:03.438 --> 00:18:04.498
deprived neighborhoods,

298
00:18:05.498 --> 00:18:08.198
and I would only start screening in people whose

299
00:18:09.138 --> 00:18:12.638
age was divisible by five, so as to create a natural

300
00:18:12.658 --> 00:18:16.578
experiment that would generate rigorous results on the impact of MCED

301
00:18:16.638 --> 00:18:17.678
screening on cancer

302
00:18:17.738 --> 00:18:22.398
mortality.We

303
00:18:22.458 --> 00:18:25.958
have a multi-cancer screening test that finds cancers in about one in

304
00:18:26.138 --> 00:18:30.098
200 people screened. That is one in 200 people

305
00:18:30.478 --> 00:18:32.378
for whom there was no cause for concern.

306
00:18:33.478 --> 00:18:37.118
Of those who test positive, over half have cancer

307
00:18:37.138 --> 00:18:37.758
diagnosed.

308
00:18:38.938 --> 00:18:42.678
In NHS gallery, there was a substantial reduction in cancers diagnosed through

309
00:18:42.718 --> 00:18:44.338
emergency room presentation.

310
00:18:45.598 --> 00:18:47.818
Technologies improve year on year.

311
00:18:48.418 --> 00:18:52.258
Now is the time to work out the logistics for a wide-scale

312
00:18:52.318 --> 00:18:55.898
implementation of MCED screening, with an emphasis on

313
00:18:55.918 --> 00:18:59.738
reducing health inequalities and providing practical guidelines on

314
00:18:59.758 --> 00:19:03.508
diagnostic pathways. Whatever you think of the clinical

315
00:19:03.618 --> 00:19:07.198
utility of the current MCED test, it is hard to deny

316
00:19:07.818 --> 00:19:11.738
that the future tests will deliver a paradigm change in the way we control

317
00:19:11.758 --> 00:19:12.838
cancer. Thank you.

318
00:19:20.858 --> 00:19:22.658
Well, Peter already gave my talk, so.

319
00:19:26.138 --> 00:19:30.128
I want to thank Nick and the AACR for giving me this

320
00:19:30.158 --> 00:19:34.058
opportunity to talk about a revolutionary, fascinating

321
00:19:34.098 --> 00:19:37.898
topic that has occupied much of my waking

322
00:19:38.538 --> 00:19:40.418
life for the last several years.

323
00:19:41.358 --> 00:19:44.898
I'm really excited to be here, and I'm really excited to hear from all of you.

324
00:19:47.338 --> 00:19:47.718
Let's

325
00:19:49.258 --> 00:19:52.298
get started. I have no disclosures. Okay.

326
00:19:52.838 --> 00:19:56.178
Why are we susceptible to hype about MCEDs?

327
00:19:57.378 --> 00:19:59.598
Probably many reasons. Here are just three.

328
00:20:00.318 --> 00:20:03.898
There is an ingrained belief that early detection is always good.

329
00:20:03.958 --> 00:20:07.858
This is an old, probably more than 50 or 60 years old, poster from the

330
00:20:07.878 --> 00:20:09.208
American Cancer Society.

331
00:20:10.258 --> 00:20:14.248
And we're justifiably excited about this technological leap that

332
00:20:14.638 --> 00:20:18.478
could enable us to find cancers that don't have existing screening tests,

333
00:20:18.998 --> 00:20:22.918
many of which are kind of intractable, and there's really hope that early

334
00:20:22.978 --> 00:20:24.388
detection will change that.

335
00:20:25.518 --> 00:20:26.078
And the third

336
00:20:27.338 --> 00:20:30.458
reason here is that we are optimists.

337
00:20:31.038 --> 00:20:34.898
If we think we extrapolate from diagnostic performance

338
00:20:35.138 --> 00:20:38.998
to expectation of benefit. If a test can find the

339
00:20:39.058 --> 00:20:42.398
cancer, the test should be able to save that cancer.

340
00:20:43.558 --> 00:20:44.918
And we know better.

341
00:20:45.998 --> 00:20:46.258
I think

342
00:20:47.158 --> 00:20:51.018
I'm not even going to go through these counters, but the world

343
00:20:51.038 --> 00:20:54.618
doesn't know better. The person on the street does not know better, the person

344
00:20:54.638 --> 00:20:58.158
who's going to be making decisions about how to screen in this new

345
00:20:58.258 --> 00:20:58.638
era.

346
00:21:00.198 --> 00:21:00.498
And

347
00:21:01.798 --> 00:21:05.538
I have to start with the tale of ovarian cancer because

348
00:21:06.398 --> 00:21:10.058
I began my career working on CA125.

349
00:21:10.138 --> 00:21:13.918
I was fascinated by biomarkers for cancer

350
00:21:13.998 --> 00:21:17.818
screening. It was the first biomarker, but really there was no data because ovarian

351
00:21:17.858 --> 00:21:21.728
cancer is so rare. And fortunately, I turned around and there was another

352
00:21:21.738 --> 00:21:25.438
biomarker, PSA, and I spent much of my career working on prostate

353
00:21:25.478 --> 00:21:29.298
cancer. The issues of biomarkers, how you can use biomarkers,

354
00:21:29.418 --> 00:21:33.178
the options that you have when using biomarkers to screen, how to

355
00:21:33.238 --> 00:21:36.698
optimize that, how to understand how biomarkers

356
00:21:37.118 --> 00:21:40.678
evolve over time with disease, natural history, all of that was fascinating to

357
00:21:40.718 --> 00:21:44.398
me. But ovarian cancer is a poster child because there was a great

358
00:21:44.438 --> 00:21:48.318
biomarker, and it was made even better by the development of a personalized

359
00:21:48.378 --> 00:21:52.078
test, the ROCA algorithm, that had fantastic diagnostic performance

360
00:21:52.418 --> 00:21:55.678
and ultimately made it to a large screening trial in the United Kingdom.

361
00:21:56.518 --> 00:22:00.158
Two screening arms, one that used the ROCA algorithm, the

362
00:22:00.198 --> 00:22:04.138
CA125 MMS, mixed modality, CA125

363
00:22:04.158 --> 00:22:07.138
followed by ultrasound, and an ultrasound arm only,

364
00:22:07.798 --> 00:22:10.278
and none of them showed mortality benefit.

365
00:22:11.538 --> 00:22:15.498
And it's so poignant because right at the time that this trial was published and

366
00:22:15.578 --> 00:22:19.378
showed that our optimism about benefit

367
00:22:19.418 --> 00:22:23.268
based on performance had not borne out, right at that point of

368
00:22:23.298 --> 00:22:26.838
disappointment, the hype cycle about multi-cancer early

369
00:22:26.878 --> 00:22:30.858
detection started. And I kept saying, "We need to figure out what went wrong

370
00:22:30.918 --> 00:22:34.838
in that trial, before we launch." And so

371
00:22:34.858 --> 00:22:37.998
for the next several years, we tried to figure out what went wrong in that trial.

372
00:22:38.658 --> 00:22:42.318
Which, by the way, was a fantastic success as a trial, provided incredible

373
00:22:42.378 --> 00:22:46.368
information, made me think, "What makes a successful

374
00:22:46.438 --> 00:22:47.558
trial?" We can talk about that.

375
00:22:50.118 --> 00:22:53.238
So, three lessons in the short time that I have.

376
00:22:53.838 --> 00:22:57.648
How do we go from hype to hope? How do we go from having our heads in the

377
00:22:57.718 --> 00:23:00.998
clouds to our feet in the ground and making good decisions going forward?

378
00:23:01.418 --> 00:23:03.978
Because harm of a test is not just the individual harm.

379
00:23:04.408 --> 00:23:08.198
Harm is also system and societal harm, of putting out a test that

380
00:23:08.278 --> 00:23:10.618
actually you think will work and doesn't work.

381
00:23:10.938 --> 00:23:14.558
That is not good for our health system, and it's not good for society.

382
00:23:14.798 --> 00:23:18.108
Maybe not bad at the individual level, having a useless test, but

383
00:23:18.898 --> 00:23:22.638
very bad for society, particularly if they're related to the costs.

384
00:23:23.438 --> 00:23:25.238
So, how do we keep our feet on the ground?

385
00:23:25.318 --> 00:23:27.318
The first one is about diagnostic performance.

386
00:23:27.658 --> 00:23:31.458
The diagnostic performance studies are dizzying, is so hard

387
00:23:31.838 --> 00:23:34.098
to know what to make of a diagnostic performance study.

388
00:23:34.998 --> 00:23:38.858
Then, once we kind of really understand what we need to know and take

389
00:23:38.918 --> 00:23:40.198
out of these diagnostic studies,

390
00:23:41.058 --> 00:23:44.678
can we predict whether finding a cancer will help a cancer?

391
00:23:45.058 --> 00:23:48.878
What's going to bridge from performance to, I'll just say down staging

392
00:23:49.158 --> 00:23:53.138
to earlier to diagnosis. And finally, we need to know

393
00:23:53.178 --> 00:23:56.938
how to interpret studies with down staging outcomes, because the gallery trial is

394
00:23:57.858 --> 00:24:01.618
really the first randomized efficacy trial with a down staging

395
00:24:01.678 --> 00:24:05.638
outcome rather than mortality. And we have not been

396
00:24:05.698 --> 00:24:08.578
in that game until now, and we have got a lot to learn.

397
00:24:09.958 --> 00:24:13.598
Okay, diagnostic performance statistics, dizzying. They can really feed the hype.

398
00:24:14.218 --> 00:24:16.978
I'm telling you this from experience.

399
00:24:17.118 --> 00:24:21.018
I speak to many reporters. I'm always giving them diagnostic performance

400
00:24:21.078 --> 00:24:24.950
statistics lessons.And one, I don't have time to talk

401
00:24:25.010 --> 00:24:28.430
about all of these, but the one that I think is really confounding for people

402
00:24:29.050 --> 00:24:32.050
is the positive predictive value versus sensitivity.

403
00:24:32.790 --> 00:24:35.890
The formula's at the bottom. One is the flip side of the other.

404
00:24:36.230 --> 00:24:39.590
One is the probability of cancer given you have a test, and the other is the

405
00:24:39.630 --> 00:24:43.210
probability you have a positive test, probability you have a positive test given

406
00:24:43.250 --> 00:24:44.070
that you have cancer.

407
00:24:45.470 --> 00:24:47.110
How can the public navigate this, right?

408
00:24:47.790 --> 00:24:51.630
So cancer cases are a small minority of individuals tested, and it is very

409
00:24:51.670 --> 00:24:55.430
important when you put your net into that pool to diagnose individuals that you

410
00:24:55.470 --> 00:24:59.370
don't net too many non-cancers. And the PPV tells

411
00:24:59.410 --> 00:25:01.390
you how successful you've been with that.

412
00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:05.150
The PPV is how well you've done in the non-cancers, not pulling them

413
00:25:05.230 --> 00:25:09.000
out along with the cancers. But sensitivity is

414
00:25:09.090 --> 00:25:10.390
how you're doing with the cancers.

415
00:25:10.650 --> 00:25:12.810
Have you found them, and have you found them early?

416
00:25:13.190 --> 00:25:15.070
And here's an example of how confused people get.

417
00:25:15.470 --> 00:25:19.250
Headline, experimental blood test shows promise for detecting cancers earlier.

418
00:25:19.850 --> 00:25:21.930
Entire article is about the PPV.

419
00:25:22.930 --> 00:25:26.840
You would be forgiven for thinking that the sensitivity of the test in Pathfinder 2

420
00:25:26.870 --> 00:25:30.090
was 60%. In fact, overall, it was 40%.

421
00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:34.160
In that set of cancers that Peter talked about was a subset of the

422
00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:34.710
cancers.

423
00:25:35.630 --> 00:25:38.710
Okay? That over all the cancers, it was 40%.

424
00:25:39.130 --> 00:25:41.460
Of a smaller subset, it was higher.

425
00:25:42.490 --> 00:25:46.140
The point is that you could be forgiven for thinking that the test was

426
00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:48.130
60% sensitive from this article.

427
00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:53.850
Now, sensitivity, which really is the key, can be so

428
00:25:53.870 --> 00:25:57.770
confusing. And Peter talked about sensitivity being a challenge

429
00:25:57.790 --> 00:26:01.510
because sensitivity really depends on the type of study that you're doing

430
00:26:01.910 --> 00:26:05.870
and the mix of cancers and the mix of stages of those

431
00:26:05.910 --> 00:26:09.840
cancers. So this is one test, the Galleri

432
00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:13.290
test, three studies, diagnostic test, where you

433
00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:17.070
have basically a convenient sample of cases, you know they have

434
00:26:17.130 --> 00:26:17.510
cancer,

435
00:26:18.890 --> 00:26:22.770
and see a sensitivity aggregate overall, 51%.

436
00:26:22.850 --> 00:26:24.810
Obviously, you have per cancer sensitivity.

437
00:26:25.150 --> 00:26:28.170
You have per stage sensitivity, which you can get from this kind of study.

438
00:26:29.270 --> 00:26:29.720
This is an

439
00:26:30.690 --> 00:26:32.610
abstract ASCO by Patel,

440
00:26:33.770 --> 00:26:34.070
et al.,

441
00:26:34.930 --> 00:26:38.170
that was one year before diagnosis, and this is Pathfinder

442
00:26:38.270 --> 00:26:42.230
overall. And so Pathfinder is an intended use

443
00:26:42.310 --> 00:26:45.890
population. Asymptomatic people come get screened, follow for a

444
00:26:46.010 --> 00:26:49.810
year and see, and estimate a sensitivity from

445
00:26:49.890 --> 00:26:53.530
that design and that mix of cancers and that population.

446
00:26:53.540 --> 00:26:55.910
And you can see we have apples and oranges here.

447
00:26:55.970 --> 00:26:59.940
Very, very difficult for the public to understand sensitivity when

448
00:26:59.940 --> 00:27:03.170
there's multiple different measures of sensitivity.

449
00:27:03.470 --> 00:27:07.130
We have a paper where we say, "Let's figure out a new

450
00:27:07.490 --> 00:27:11.430
lexicon for sensitivity, different terms for

451
00:27:11.470 --> 00:27:14.670
each type." Now, what really matters with benefit?

452
00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:18.910
What matters is you need early-stage sensitivity in the intended use

453
00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:22.590
population. Guess what? You can't easily measure it.

454
00:27:23.850 --> 00:27:26.290
This is a version of sensitivity overall.

455
00:27:26.590 --> 00:27:29.090
It's actually a proxy for sensitivity.

456
00:27:29.530 --> 00:27:32.210
There is no stage-specific version of that.

457
00:27:33.030 --> 00:27:36.950
Very, very hard. All we really have stage-specific and cancer type-specific

458
00:27:37.330 --> 00:27:41.290
is to go back to the diagnostic studies, which may well be overly

459
00:27:41.370 --> 00:27:42.030
optimistic.

460
00:27:43.070 --> 00:27:46.630
So out of all of this, we have to get a sense of what are we really

461
00:27:46.690 --> 00:27:49.810
talking about in terms of sensitivity,

462
00:27:50.750 --> 00:27:52.420
early-stage sensitivity.

463
00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:57.120
And do we think that that's going to be potentially beneficial?

464
00:27:58.870 --> 00:28:00.610
That's what's key for clinical benefit.

465
00:28:02.150 --> 00:28:05.940
But now we have to take that and think about,

466
00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:07.859
is it going to give us downstaging?

467
00:28:08.930 --> 00:28:12.150
Even if we have a value of 74%,

468
00:28:13.390 --> 00:28:15.190
which I think was actually

469
00:28:16.550 --> 00:28:18.830
influenced by stage mix. I

470
00:28:19.670 --> 00:28:22.530
don't know. We don't know what the stage of those cancers were, but I think that

471
00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:26.260
later stage cancers will lead to, if you have a pool of later stage cancers, you'll

472
00:28:26.290 --> 00:28:29.650
have higher sensitivity. What drives translation from performance to

473
00:28:29.710 --> 00:28:30.390
downstaging?

474
00:28:31.230 --> 00:28:34.270
Natural history. What's going on beneath the hood?

475
00:28:36.090 --> 00:28:39.410
I got to introduce this jargon because I'll probably use it

476
00:28:39.470 --> 00:28:43.209
later, the sojourn time, which is the time from

477
00:28:43.269 --> 00:28:46.990
detectable onset to diagnosis. That's kind of the general

478
00:28:47.090 --> 00:28:50.750
opportunity for detecting a cancer before it presents.

479
00:28:51.580 --> 00:28:55.130
But what we want is the early stage opportunity, the opportunity in early

480
00:28:55.250 --> 00:28:55.630
stage.

481
00:28:56.590 --> 00:28:58.290
How do we learn about opportunity?

482
00:28:58.710 --> 00:28:59.590
We compare

483
00:29:00.470 --> 00:29:03.470
incidents. We look at the change in incidents under screening.

484
00:29:04.810 --> 00:29:06.260
Can everyone guess what this cancer is?

485
00:29:06.330 --> 00:29:08.830
Right, that's prostate cancer after the introduction of PSA.

486
00:29:09.230 --> 00:29:11.960
This is a hypothetical screening trial where you've got interval and

487
00:29:12.010 --> 00:29:15.810
screen-detected cases. And when you see how incidence changes

488
00:29:15.910 --> 00:29:19.570
under screening, that tells you about what's going on beneath the hood.

489
00:29:20.090 --> 00:29:23.530
Incidence changes a lot. There's a lot of prevalent cancer.

490
00:29:23.570 --> 00:29:25.860
There's a long opportunity for detection.

491
00:29:25.870 --> 00:29:28.350
But we want early-stage opportunity.

492
00:29:28.370 --> 00:29:31.870
So we need incidence patterns by stage. And so we...

493
00:29:33.270 --> 00:29:36.270
I'm going to keep going. We need incidence patterns by stage.

494
00:29:36.850 --> 00:29:39.170
So we need to have screened cohorts to learn this.

495
00:29:39.640 --> 00:29:43.219
And so this is work that we did in the UKC-TOCS trial, where we looked

496
00:29:43.410 --> 00:29:45.590
at incidence patterns for early and late.

497
00:29:45.690 --> 00:29:49.400
Here we've got two arms, the mixed modality and ultrasound,

498
00:29:49.810 --> 00:29:51.910
and we have screen-detected cancers,

499
00:29:52.810 --> 00:29:55.850
early and late, and interval-detected cancers, early and late.

500
00:29:56.210 --> 00:30:00.070
And then we can learn the early stage opportunity, the duration that the

501
00:30:00.130 --> 00:30:03.930
cancer spends in early stage, and we can also learn the

502
00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:07.970
late stage opportunity, how long the cancer is in late stage.

